<p>The words "paycheck" and "pay stub" get used interchangeably in everyday conversation, but they refer to different documents with different purposes. If you searched for "paycheck template," you may actually want a pay stub (the earnings record), a check (the payment instrument), or possibly both. This page clarifies the difference and gives you the right tool for what you actually need.</p>

<h2>Paycheck vs. Pay Stub: What Each Document Is</h2>

<p>A <strong>paycheck</strong> is a literal payment instrument -- a paper check that transfers money from the employer's bank account to the employee's bank account. It has the employer's name, the employee's name, the payment amount, the date, a check number, and the bank's routing and account numbers in the MICR line at the bottom. A paycheck's fundamental purpose is to transfer money. You endorse it and deposit it, or take it to a bank and cash it.</p>

<p>A <strong>pay stub</strong> (also called an earnings statement or paycheck stub) is the earnings record that accompanies or references the paycheck. It shows the breakdown of how the gross pay amount was calculated and what deductions were taken out to arrive at the net pay amount on the check. Pay stubs show hourly rate and hours worked (for hourly employees), each type of deduction itemized separately, and year-to-date totals for all categories.</p>

<p>In the era of paper paychecks, the stub was literally attached to the check -- a tear-off portion at the top or side that the employee kept as their record after cashing or depositing the check. That is where the term "pay stub" (stub = the part left over after the check is detached) comes from. The check stub was proof of the payment without being the payment instrument itself.</p>

<h2>The Direct Deposit Era and Why "Paycheck" Persists</h2>

<p>Today, the vast majority of employees in the United States receive their wages via direct deposit -- electronic transfer directly into their bank account. According to the American Payroll Association, over 93% of employees use direct deposit. There is no paper check in this transaction. There is no physical stub to tear off.</p>

<p>Yet we still call the payment a "paycheck." The term survives because it describes the concept of a wage payment, even though the physical check rarely exists. When your boss says "paychecks go out Friday," they mean direct deposits post Friday. "Where's my paycheck?" means "why hasn't my direct deposit cleared?" Language lags behind technology by decades.</p>

<p>What has replaced the physical stub in the direct deposit era is an electronic pay statement -- a PDF or portal entry that shows all the same information the old stub showed, but delivered digitally. This is what this tool generates: an electronic earnings statement in a standard professional format, the same document that payroll services like ADP, Paychex, and Gusto generate for employees each pay period.</p>

<h2>Who Searches for "Paycheck Template"</h2>

<p>Based on the diverse population of people who look for paycheck templates, there are a few distinct groups:</p>

<p><strong>Small business owners needing to pay employees:</strong> A small business owner with one or two employees who has been paying them cash or informal check wants to formalize their payroll documentation. They need a template that shows the employer paying the employee with proper deductions documented. The generator on this page serves this use case -- you can enter the employer name (your business) and the employee's information to produce a properly formatted earnings statement.</p>

<p><strong>Self-employed workers needing proof of income:</strong> Freelancers, consultants, and sole proprietors who effectively "pay themselves" from their business income need to show third parties (landlords, lenders) that they have regular income. They search "paycheck template" because they want something that represents their income in a formal format, even though technically they receive distributions from their business rather than a paycheck from an employer. The generator handles this case -- use your business name as employer and your name as employee.</p>

<p><strong>Workers who lost access to their employer's pay portal:</strong> Someone who left a job and can no longer log in to the company's HR portal to retrieve old pay stubs, or a worker whose employer's portal is not functioning, may search for a template to reconstruct documentation of past income. For past periods, you would need to enter the historical gross pay amounts accurately based on your own records.</p>

<p><strong>People trying to understand what a paycheck contains:</strong> Some searchers want to understand what information appears on a paycheck stub and why. This page and the linked resources below explain every field in detail.</p>

<h2>What Belongs on a Pay Stub (Not a Paycheck)</h2>

<p>If you actually need an earnings statement (what most people mean when they search for "paycheck template"), here is what a complete one contains:</p>

<p><strong>Employer information:</strong> Full legal name of the employer, employer's business address, and optionally the employer's EIN (federal Employer Identification Number). The employer's name and address appear at the top of a standard pay stub layout.</p>

<p><strong>Employee information:</strong> Employee's full legal name (matching tax documents), employee address, employee ID or the last four digits of the Social Security Number, and sometimes job title or department.</p>

<p><strong>Pay period and pay date:</strong> The start date and end date of the pay period this stub covers. The pay date -- when the money was actually transferred -- is typically 3-5 days after the pay period end for payroll processing. These dates must be realistic and internally consistent across multiple stubs.</p>

<p><strong>Earnings section:</strong> For salaried employees, gross pay per period equals annual salary divided by pay periods per year (26 for bi-weekly, 24 for semi-monthly, 12 for monthly, 52 for weekly). For hourly employees, gross pay equals regular hours multiplied by hourly rate, plus overtime hours multiplied by rate times 1.5 for hours over 40 per week. The earnings section shows each type of earnings separately with the calculation behind it.</p>

<p><strong>Deductions section:</strong> Every mandatory and voluntary deduction appears here, each labeled and itemized separately. Mandatory deductions include federal income tax (calculated using IRS bracket tables), Social Security (6.2%), Medicare (1.45%), and state income tax (varies by state). Voluntary pre-tax deductions include 401(k) contributions, health insurance premiums, FSA contributions, and HSA contributions. Voluntary post-tax deductions include Roth 401(k), supplemental life insurance, and union dues.</p>

<p><strong>Net pay:</strong> Gross pay minus total deductions. This is the amount that hits the employee's bank account on pay day. On a physical check, this is the written amount on the check. On a direct deposit, it is the transferred amount.</p>

<p><strong>Year-to-date totals:</strong> Running totals for the calendar year for gross pay, each deduction category, and net pay. YTD figures are critical for tax filing and for lenders who want to verify income consistency over time.</p>

<h2>The Pay Stub as a Financial Document</h2>

<p>Pay stubs serve as critical financial documentation for several major life events:</p>

<p><strong>Apartment applications:</strong> Landlords use pay stubs to verify that a prospective tenant earns enough to afford the rent -- typically they look for monthly income equal to 2.5 to 3 times the monthly rent. They want to see recent stubs (last 2-3 pay periods), consistent income, and a clean employer relationship. See our <a href="/pay-stub-for-apartment">pay stub for apartment applications</a> guide for what different landlord types require.</p>

<p><strong>Mortgage applications:</strong> Mortgage underwriters use pay stubs to verify gross income, employment status, and the reliability of the income stream. For W-2 employees, the standard package is pay stubs plus two years of W-2s plus two months of bank statements. For self-employed borrowers, the requirements are more extensive. See the <a href="/pay-stub-for-mortgage">pay stub for mortgage</a> guide for loan-type-specific requirements.</p>

<p><strong>Personal loan and auto loan applications:</strong> Lenders verify income to assess debt-to-income ratios and repayment capacity. Recent pay stubs are the primary income verification document for most consumer lending. For auto loans specifically, dealers often pull pay stubs in the finance office as part of the credit application process.</p>

<p><strong>Government benefit applications:</strong> Medicaid, SNAP, housing assistance, and other need-based programs require income verification. Pay stubs are the standard documentation for employed applicants. Some programs accept earnings statements from the past 30 days; others want the most recent month.</p>

<p><strong>Child support and alimony calculations:</strong> Family court proceedings often require detailed income documentation. Pay stubs showing gross pay and all deductions are the starting point for income calculations in divorce, support, and custody proceedings.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Paycheck Templates</h2>

<h3>Is there a difference between a "paycheck stub" and a "pay stub"?</h3>
<p>No. They are the same document. "Paycheck stub" is the longer form that references the historical origin (the stub attached to the paper check). "Pay stub" is the more common short form used today. "Earnings statement" and "paycheck statement" are also synonymous. All of these terms refer to the earnings record showing gross pay, deductions, and net pay for a specific pay period.</p>

<h3>Can I generate a paycheck template that shows a paper check image?</h3>
<p>This generator produces an earnings statement (pay stub), not a paper check image. A paper check image includes the check number, the bank routing and account numbers, and the signature line -- none of which are relevant to income verification documentation. What landlords and lenders need is the earnings statement, not the check itself. If you need to verify a payment was made, a bank statement showing the deposit is typically more appropriate than a check image.</p>

<h3>I received a paper check from my employer but no stub. What should I do?</h3>
<p>In states that require pay stubs (California, New York, Texas-Nevada-specific rules, Colorado, Oregon, Wisconsin, Minnesota, and several others), your employer is legally required to provide an earnings statement with each payment. Contact your employer's payroll department and request itemized earnings statements for each pay period. If they refuse, contact your state's department of labor. In states without a pay stub mandate, you can request the information, though enforcement may be limited. You can use your actual check amount and your knowledge of the pay components to generate a supplemental stub showing the details, but be accurate about the numbers.</p>

<h3>I need to show past income from a job I left. How do I get those pay stubs?</h3>
<p>The best sources for past pay stubs from a former employer are: (1) the former employer's payroll portal, which you may still have access to for a period after leaving; (2) the former employer's HR or payroll department, who can reissue electronic copies of prior stubs; or (3) your W-2 form from that year, which shows total annual wages and taxes withheld. For mortgage and major lending applications, two years of W-2s plus recent pay stubs is the standard documentation package -- prior-year W-2s replace the need for old individual stubs.</p>

<h3>Do I need to show a paycheck template to my new employer?</h3>
<p>New employers sometimes ask for recent pay stubs from your previous employer to verify your salary history, particularly to confirm your stated previous salary for negotiation purposes. Some states (California, New York, Illinois, Massachusetts, and others) have enacted salary history ban laws that prohibit employers from asking about or using prior salary information in hiring decisions. If you are in one of these states, you are not required to provide previous pay stubs to a new employer as a condition of employment. Check whether your state has a salary history ban before complying with such a request.</p>

